          "type": "user",
          "text": "Let's work on the @dashboard/ and @react-email/ folders. I have a written plan with two options. I want you to trace a place to implement option A. When done, please, make sure to open a new branch for both projects, commit the changes, push to remote, and open a PR. The dashboard PR should be against `main`. The react-email PR should be against `feat/ai-oss-editor`.\n\nHere's the plan:\n\n```\n# Bubble Menu Composable Refactor — Architecture Options\n\n## Context\n\nThe editor V2 bubble menu system needs to be refactored into a composable/modular architecture that can be extracted into the `@react-email/editor` OSS package. Third-party devs should be able to: use it with zero config, customize items, swap sub-components, or replace entirely. DX is the highest priority.\n\n### Current State\n\n**OSS package** (`@react-email/editor@0.0.0-experimental.6`): provides `EmailNode`, built-in TipTap extensions (Body, Section, Button, Columns, etc.), attribute extensions. **Zero bubble menu code.**\n\n**Dashboard** (`src/components/editor-v2/ui/bubble-menu/`): 6 files, ~1140 lines total:\n- `bubble-menu.tsx` (242L) — text formatting: Bold/Italic/Underline/Strike/Code/Uppercase + alignment + NodeSelector + LinkSelector\n- `bubble-menu-image.tsx` (171L) — replace image + link\n- `bubble-menu-button.tsx` (111L) — link + style\n- `bubble-menu-link.tsx` (95L) — edit/unlink/open link\n- `link-selector.tsx` (341L) — URL input w/ variable insertion, toast, validation (most Resend-coupled)\n- `node-selector.tsx` (181L) — block type dropdown w/ Radix Popover, `@/ui/shared` styles\n\nAll mounted in `core/editor.tsx:147-153` inside `EditorContext.Provider`, gated by `isCollaborative`.\n\n### Resend-Specific Dependencies to Decouple\n\n| Dependency | Files | Strategy |\n|---|---|---|\n| `@/lib/cn` | All | Ship thin `cn` or accept `className` |\n| `@/ui/shared` dropdown styles | node-selector | className prop |\n| `@/ui/toast` | link-selector | `onError` callback |\n| `@/ui/icons/icon-variable` | link-selector | Slot/render prop |\n| `VariablesDropdown` | link-selector | Remove; inject via slot |\n| `getUrlFromString` | link-selector | Extract generic URL validator |\n| `VARIABLE_PATTERN` | link-selector | Remove from OSS |\n| `editorEventBus` (`add-link`) | bubble-menu | Move to OSS — ship generic event bus with `add-link` event |\n| `startImageUpload` | bubble-menu-image | `onReplaceImage` callback |\n| Resend Tailwind tokens (gray-a2, etc.) | All | CSS vars or unstyled |\n| `@radix-ui/react-popover` | node-selector | Peer dep or built-in |\n\n---\n\n## Inspirations\n\nThree libraries that inform this design — each solves \"composable UI primitives\" differently:\n\n| | **Radix UI** | **Base UI** | **shadcn/ui** |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **What ships** | Unstyled compound components | Unstyled components + hooks | Copy-paste styled components |\n| **Styling** | Data-attributes, bring your own CSS | Data-attributes, bring your own CSS | Tailwind classes baked in |\n| **Composition** | Tree of `<Root>`, `<Trigger>`, `<Content>` | Components OR hooks (choose your level) | Pre-composed, modify source |\n| **Customization** | Compose different children | Override via hooks or `render` prop | Edit the copied source code |\n| **API stability** | Component tree shape is the contract | Hooks are the contract, components can change | No contract — you own the code |\n| **Zero-config** | No (unstyled) | No (unstyled) | Yes (ships styled) |\n\n---\n\n## Option A: Compound Components\n\n**Closest to: Radix UI + Base UI**\n\nUnstyled composable primitives. Devs build menus by composing `<Root>`, `<Group>`, `<Button>`, `<Separator>`, etc. Data-attributes for state. Pre-composed presets for zero-config.\n\n### How it compares to each inspiration\n\n**Like Radix UI:** Tree of compound components (`BubbleMenuRoot > BubbleMenuGroup > BoldButton`). Each part renders with `data-part` and `data-state` attributes. No opinions on styling. Accessibility baked in (aria-pressed, keyboard nav). Devs compose exactly the tree shape they want.\n\n**Like Base UI:** Also ships unstyled with data-attributes, but Base UI additionally offers hooks as escape hatches for each component (e.g., `useMenu()` alongside `<Menu>`). We'd borrow this: offer `useBubbleMenu()`, `useFormattingItems()` etc. as escape hatches for devs who want full control without the component tree. This is the key differentiator from pure Radix.\n\n**Unlike shadcn/ui:** Not copy-paste. Ships as an npm package with a stable API. Default presets (`TextBubbleMenu`) provide zero-config, but devs compose from primitives for customization rather than editing source.\n\n### API\n\n```tsx\nimport {\n  // Primitives (Radix-style compound components)\n  BubbleMenuRoot, BubbleMenuGroup, BubbleMenuButton, BubbleMenuSeparator,\n  NodeSelector, NodeSelectorTrigger, NodeSelectorContent, NodeSelectorItem,\n  LinkForm, LinkFormInput, LinkFormSubmit, LinkFormUnlink,\n\n  // Pre-built formatting buttons (compose into any tree)\n  BoldButton, ItalicButton, UnderlineButton, StrikeButton,\n  CodeButton, UppercaseButton,\n  AlignLeftButton, AlignCenterButton, AlignRightButton,\n\n  // Pre-composed presets (zero-config)\n  TextBubbleMenu, LinkBubbleMenu, ImageBubbleMenu, ButtonBubbleMenu,\n\n  // Escape-hatch hooks (Base UI-style)\n  useBubbleMenu, useFormattingItems, useLinkForm,\n} from '@react-email/editor/bubble-menu';\n```\n\n### Zero-Config\n\n```tsx\nimport '@react-email/editor/bubble-menu.css';\n\n<TextBubbleMenu />\n<LinkBubbleMenu />\n<ImageBubbleMenu />\n<ButtonBubbleMenu />\n```\n\n### Custom — compose from primitives\n\n```tsx\n<BubbleMenuRoot showWhen=\"textSelection\">\n  <NodeSelector />\n  <BubbleMenuSeparator />\n  <BubbleMenuGroup>\n    <BoldButton />\n    <ItalicButton />\n    <BubbleMenuButton\n      name=\"highlight\"\n      icon={HighlightIcon}\n      isActive={(ed) => ed.isActive('highlight')}\n      command={(ed) => ed.chain().focus().toggleHighlight().run()}\n    />\n  </BubbleMenuGroup>\n  <BubbleMenuSeparator />\n  <BubbleMenuGroup>\n    <AlignLeftButton />\n    <AlignCenterButton />\n    <AlignRightButton />\n  </BubbleMenuGroup>\n</BubbleMenuRoot>\n```\n\n### Custom — escape hatch via hooks (Base UI pattern)\n\n```tsx\nfunction MyBubbleMenu() {\n  const { editor } = useCurrentEditor();\n  const { shouldShow, props } = useBubbleMenu({ excludeNodes: ['image'] });\n  const items = useFormattingItems({ exclude: ['Code'] });\n\n  return (\n    <BubbleMenu editor={editor} shouldShow={shouldShow} {...props}>\n      <div className=\"my-custom-toolbar\">\n        {items.map((item) => (\n          <button key={item.name} onClick={() => item.command(editor)}>\n            <item.icon />\n          </button>\n        ))}\n      </div>\n    </BubbleMenu>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Resend Recomposition\n\nResend wraps OSS primitives with its own `ResendNodeSelector` (gradient icons, `@/ui/shared` styles) and `ResendLinkSelector` (`VariablesDropdown`, toast):\n\n```tsx\nexport function EditorBubbleMenu({ omit = [] }) {\n  return (\n    <BubbleMenuRoot\n      showWhen=\"textSelection\"\n      excludeNodes={['image', 'button', 'htmlContent', 'socialLinks', 'youtube', 'twitter']}\n      className=\"bg-background flex w-fit divide-x divide-gray-3 rounded-xl border border-gray-3 shadow-xl\"\n    >\n      <ResendNodeSelector omit={omit} />\n      <ResendLinkSelector />\n      <BubbleMenuGroup>\n        {!omit.includes('Bold') && <BoldButton className=\"p-2 text-gray-10 hover:bg-gray-a2 ...\" />}\n        {!omit.includes('Italic') && <ItalicButton className=\"...\" />}\n        {/* ... */}\n      </BubbleMenuGroup>\n    </BubbleMenuRoot>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Pros\n- **Maximum flexibility** — any menu shape possible via tree composition\n- **Familiar mental model** — Radix + Base UI patterns React devs already know\n- **Tree-shakeable** — import only what you use\n- **Escape hatches** — hooks for when the component tree doesn't fit (Base UI pattern)\n- **Pre-composed presets** for zero-config\n\n### Cons\n- **Largest API surface** — many exports to document/maintain (~20+ components)\n- **Verbose for simple customizations** — \"remove bold\" = rebuild the tree rather than pass `exclude`\n- **Compound context management** — internal context between Root/Group/Button adds complexity\n- **Resend's recomposition is medium-effort** — must rebuild tree with custom className on each primitive\n\n---\n\n## Option B: Headless Hooks + Default UI\n\n**Closest to: shadcn/ui + Base UI hooks**\n\nHooks are the stable API contract. Default components work out of the box and are trivially replaceable. The hooks/components split is similar to how Base UI offers both, but the philosophy leans shadcn/ui: components are reference implementations, not sacred primitives.\n\n### How it compares to each inspiration\n\n**Like shadcn/ui:** Ships pre-composed, styled components that work out of the box. The difference: these live in the npm package (not copy-paste), but the mental model is the same — \"here's a working component, swap parts as needed.\" Default components are thin wrappers around hooks, easy to rewrite.\n\n**Like Base UI hooks:** The hooks (`useBubbleMenu`, `useFormattingItems`, `useLinkForm`) are the real API surface. They extract all logic — visibility, state, editor commands — so devs can render whatever UI they want. This is exactly Base UI's hook philosophy: \"use the component for convenience, drop to the hook for full control.\"\n\n**Unlike Radix UI:** Not a compound component tree. No `<Root>` / `<Trigger>` / `<Content>` nesting requirement. Devs don't compose a specific tree shape — they call hooks and render freely. Simpler mental model but less \"structural.\"\n\n### API\n\n```tsx\nimport {\n  // Hooks (stable contract — Base UI pattern)\n  useBubbleMenu, useFormattingItems, useAlignmentItems,\n  useNodeSelectorItems, useLinkForm,\n\n  // Default components (shadcn/ui pattern — reference implementations)\n  TextBubbleMenu, LinkBubbleMenu, ImageBubbleMenu, ButtonBubbleMenu,\n  BubbleMenuButton, NodeSelector, LinkForm,\n\n  // Convenience button components (composable like Option A)\n  BoldButton, ItalicButton, UnderlineButton, StrikeButton,\n  CodeButton, UppercaseButton,\n  AlignLeftButton, AlignCenterButton, AlignRightButton,\n} from '@react-email/editor/bubble-menu';\n```\n\n### Hook Signatures\n\n```tsx\nuseBubbleMenu(options?: {\n  showWhen?: 'textSelection' | 'nodeSelection' | ((editor) => boolean);\n  excludeNodes?: string[];\n  placement?: 'top' | 'bottom';\n}): { shouldShow, bubbleMenuProps }\n\nuseFormattingItems(options?: {\n  exclude?: string[];\n  extra?: BubbleMenuItemConfig[];\n}): BubbleMenuItemConfig[]\n\nuseAlignmentItems(options?: {\n  exclude?: string[];\n}): BubbleMenuItemConfig[]\n\nuseLinkForm(options?: {\n  element?: 'link' | 'button' | 'image';\n  validateUrl?: (url: string) => string | null;\n  onError?: (message: string) => void;\n}): { inputRef, inputValue, setInputValue, hasLink, handleSubmit, handleUnlink }\n```\n\n### Zero-Config\n\n```tsx\nimport '@react-email/editor/bubble-menu.css';\n\n<TextBubbleMenu />\n<LinkBubbleMenu />\n<ImageBubbleMenu />\n<ButtonBubbleMenu />\n```\n\n### Custom — config-level tweaks (shadcn/ui feel)\n\n```tsx\n<TextBubbleMenu\n  exclude={['Code', 'Uppercase']}\n  excludeNodes={['image', 'button']}\n/>\n```\n\n### Custom — drop to hooks (Base UI feel)\n\n```tsx\nfunction MyBubbleMenu() {\n  const { editor } = useCurrentEditor();\n  const { shouldShow, bubbleMenuProps } = useBubbleMenu({\n    excludeNodes: ['image', 'button'],\n  });\n  const items = useFormattingItems({\n    exclude: ['Code', 'Uppercase'],\n    extra: [{\n      name: 'Highlight', icon: HighlightIcon,\n      isActive: (ed) => ed.isActive('highlight'),\n      command: (ed) => ed.chain().focus().toggleHighlight().run(),\n    }],\n  });\n\n  return (\n    <BubbleMenu editor={editor} shouldShow={shouldShow} {...bubbleMenuProps}>\n      <div className=\"my-toolbar\">\n        {items.map((item) => (\n          <BubbleMenuButton key={item.name} item={item} editor={editor} />\n        ))}\n      </div>\n    </BubbleMenu>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Resend Recomposition\n\nCurrent dashboard code already follows \"build items array, render in loop\" — maps directly to hooks:\n\n```tsx\nexport function EditorBubbleMenu({ omit = [] }) {\n  const { shouldShow, bubbleMenuProps } = useBubbleMenu({\n    excludeNodes: ['image', 'button', 'htmlContent', 'socialLinks', 'youtube', 'twitter'],\n  });\n  const formatItems = useFormattingItems({ exclude: omit });\n  const alignItems = useAlignmentItems({ exclude: omit });\n\n  return (\n    <BubbleMenu shouldShow={shouldShow} {...bubbleMenuProps}\n      className=\"bg-background flex w-fit divide-x divide-gray-3 rounded-xl ...\">\n      <ResendNodeSelector omit={omit} />\n      <ResendLinkSelector />\n      <div className=\"flex\">\n        {formatItems.map(item => (\n          <button key={item.name} className=\"p-2 text-gray-10 hover:bg-gray-a2 ...\"\n            onClick={() => item.command(editor)}>\n            <item.icon className=\"h-4 w-4\" />\n          </button>\n        ))}\n      </div>\n    </BubbleMenu>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n`ResendLinkSelector` wraps `useLinkForm` with `VariablesDropdown` + `showToast`:\n\n```tsx\nfunction ResendLinkSelector() {\n  const linkForm = useLinkForm({\n    validateUrl: getUrlFromString,\n    onError: (msg) => showToast({ title: msg, appearance: 'red' }),\n  });\n\n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={linkForm.handleSubmit}>\n      <input ref={linkForm.inputRef} value={linkForm.inputValue}\n        onChange={(e) => linkForm.setInputValue(e.target.value)} />\n      <VariablesDropdown onVariableSelect={(v) => linkForm.setInputValue(prev => prev + v)}>\n        <button><IconVariable /></button>\n      </VariablesDropdown>\n    </form>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Pros\n- **Best DX balance** — config props for beginners, hooks for power users (shadcn + Base UI)\n- **Cleanest decoupling** — `useLinkForm(validateUrl, onError)` naturally separates Resend concerns\n- **Smallest migration effort** — current \"items array → render loop\" maps directly to hooks\n- **Stable API** — hooks are the contract (Base UI), components can evolve freely\n- **Simple customizations are easy** — `exclude={['Code']}` on presets, no tree rebuild needed\n\n### Cons\n- **\"Swap one button's icon\"** still needs either a render loop or using individual `BoldButton` etc.\n- **Two mental models** — presets vs hooks (but this is the same trade-off Base UI makes)\n- **Less compositionally expressive** than compound components for novel menu layouts\n\n---\n\n## Comparison Matrix\n\n| Scenario | Option A (Compound) | Option B (Hooks + UI) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Zero-config usage | Same — `<TextBubbleMenu />` | Same — `<TextBubbleMenu />` |\n| Remove one item | Rebuild tree without that button | `exclude={['Bold']}` on preset |\n| Add custom item | `<BubbleMenuButton>` in tree | `extra: [...]` on hook |\n| Custom layout | Compose tree freely | Drop to hooks, render freely |\n| Replace LinkSelector | Swap `<LinkForm>` subtree | Wrap `useLinkForm` hook |\n| Full custom menu | Use hooks (escape hatch) | Use hooks (primary path) |\n| API surface size | ~20+ components + hooks | ~5 hooks + 4 presets + buttons |\n| Closest inspiration | Radix UI (+ Base UI escape hatches) | shadcn/ui + Base UI hooks |\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation: Option B (Headless Hooks + Default UI)\n\n**Why:**\n1. **Migration is mechanical** — current code already follows \"items array → render loop\" pattern; hooks formalize it\n2. **Hardest decoupling (LinkSelector)** is cleanest with `useLinkForm(validateUrl, onError)` callbacks\n3. **Simple customizations stay simple** — `exclude` prop on presets vs rebuilding a component tree\n4. **Hooks are the most natural React DX** — familiar to any React dev, aligns with Base UI's proven approach\n5. **Smaller API surface** — fewer concepts to document and maintain\n6. **Aligns with `@react-email/editor`** existing pattern — extensions are config, UI is separate\n\n**Borrowed from Option A:** Also export individual button components (`BoldButton`, `ItalicButton`, etc.) as thin wrappers, giving a composition path without requiring full hook usage for simple cases.\n\n---\n\n## Event Bus (OSS scope)\n\nThe editor event bus moves to the OSS package as a generic, type-safe pub/sub system. The `add-link` event is shipped as a built-in event.\n\n### Current flow (Resend dashboard)\n1. `extensions/link.ts:102` — `Mod-k` dispatches `editorEventBus.dispatch('add-link', undefined)`\n2. `ui/bubble-menu/bubble-menu.tsx:77` — subscribes via `editorEventBus.on('add-link', ...)` → opens `LinkSelector`\n\n### OSS implementation\n\n**Event bus class** — extract from `core/event-bus.ts` as-is (already generic, well-typed, uses `CustomEvent` + `AbortController`). Change prefix from `@resend/editor:` to `@react-email/editor:`.\n\n**Built-in event map** — ship `add-link` in the base `EditorEventMap`:\n```ts\nexport interface EditorEventMap {\n  'add-link': undefined;\n}\n```\n\n**Extensibility** — third-party devs extend via module augmentation (pattern already established):\n```ts\ndeclare module '@react-email/editor' {\n  interface EditorEventMap {\n    'my-custom-event': { data: string };\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Link extension** — the `Mod-k` keyboard shortcut + `add-link` dispatch moves into the OSS `Link` extension. The dashboard's `link.ts` extends the OSS version (adds `ses:no-track`, `processStylesForUnlink`, custom `parseHTML`).\n\n### Files involved\n- **OSS (new):** `packages/editor/src/event-bus.ts` — extracted from dashboard `core/event-bus.ts`\n- **OSS (new):** `packages/editor/src/types.ts` — `EditorEventMap` with `add-link`, event bus types\n- **OSS (modify):** `packages/editor/src/extensions/link.ts` — add `Mod-k` shortcut that dispatches `add-link`\n- **Dashboard (modify):** `src/components/editor-v2/core/event-bus.ts` — re-export from `@react-email/editor`\n- **Dashboard (modify):** `src/components/editor-v2/extensions/link.ts` — extend OSS Link, keep Resend-specific logic\n\n---\n\n## Styling Strategy\n\nSince `@react-email/editor` currently ships zero CSS and the bubble menu must work out of the box with great DX, here are the trade-offs:\n\n| Approach | Zero-Config DX | Customization | Framework Lock-in |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Unstyled + data-attributes** | Bad (looks broken) | Full control | None |\n| **CSS custom properties file** | Good (import CSS) | Override vars | None |\n| **Tailwind classes** | Good (if Tailwind) | className swap | Tailwind required |\n| **Inline styles** | Good (no imports) | style prop | None, but limited (no hover/dark) |\n\n### Recommended: Data-attributes + optional CSS import\n\nComponents render with `data-part` and `data-state` attributes. Ship an optional CSS file.\n\n**Three tiers of customization:**\n\n```tsx\n// Tier 1: Zero config — import CSS, use component\nimport '@react-email/editor/bubble-menu.css';\nimport { TextBubbleMenu } from '@react-email/editor/bubble-menu';\n<TextBubbleMenu />\n\n// Tier 2: Theme — import CSS, override a few vars\nimport '@react-email/editor/bubble-menu.css';\n// In your CSS: :root { --ree-bg: #1a1a1a; --ree-border: #333; }\n<TextBubbleMenu />\n\n// Tier 3: Full custom — skip CSS import, use className or data-attributes\n<TextBubbleMenu className=\"my-custom-toolbar\" />\n// Or target: [data-part=\"bubble-menu-button\"][data-active] { ... }\n```\n\n**Why this works best:**\n- No CSS framework dependency (works with Tailwind, vanilla CSS, CSS-in-JS, etc.)\n- Zero-config path looks good out of the box\n- CSS variables enable theming without touching component code\n- `className` prop provides full escape hatch for Tailwind users\n- Data-attributes give semantic hooks for any styling approach\n- Aligns with Radix UI's styling philosophy (which React devs already know)\n\n**CSS variables shipped:**\n```css\n:root {\n  --ree-bubble-bg: #fff;\n  --ree-bubble-border: #e5e5e5;\n  --ree-bubble-shadow: 0 4px 12px rgba(0,0,0,.08);\n  --ree-bubble-radius: 12px;\n  --ree-bubble-btn-hover: rgba(0,0,0,.04);\n  --ree-bubble-btn-active: rgba(0,0,0,.08);\n  --ree-bubble-btn-text: #6b6b6b;\n  --ree-bubble-btn-text-active: #171717;\n  --ree-bubble-separator: #e5e5e5;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Resolved Questions\n\n1. **`@react-email/editor` is a separate repo**, published on NPM. Implementation happens there; dashboard consumes via version bump.\n2. **Styling:** Data-attributes + optional CSS file with CSS custom properties (see above).\n3. **No additional bubble menus** planned beyond text/link/image/button.\n4. **`editorEventBus` `add-link` event moves to OSS.** The `Mod-k` → bubble menu communication should be part of the OSS package so third-party devs get keyboard shortcut support out of the box.\n5. **`ImageBubbleMenu`** ships a default browser file picker for \"replace image\". Devs who want custom upload behavior can override via `onReplaceImage` callback.\n6. **`isCollaborative` guard removed from OSS.** Bubble menus always render by default. Devs can add their own visibility guards via `shouldShow` or wrapping conditionals. \n```\n\nUse your superpower skills to make it happen.",
